Lisinopril is an angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitor (ACEI), preventing the conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II.[A184781,A184808] This action prevents myocyte hypertrophy and vascular smooth muscle cell proliferation seen in untreated patients.[A184808] Increased levels of bradykinin also exhibit vasodilating effects for patients taking ACEIs.[A184808] Lisinopril also inhibits renin''s conversion of angiotensin to angiotensin I.[A184817]', 'Lisinopril is an angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitor used to treat hypertension, heart failure, and myocardial infarction.[L8384,L8387,L8390] Lisinopril is not a prodrug, and functions by inhibition of angiotensin converting enzyme as well as the renin angiotensin aldosterone system.[A184781,A184808,A184817] It has a wide therapeutic index and a long duration of action as patients are generally given 10-80mg daily.[L8384,L8387,L8390]', 'DrugBank');
